  "body": "## Description\r\n\r\nPresently Lighthouse's HTTP API will return a `405 Method Not Allowed` for non-existent endpoints. I believe this behaviour is incorrect semantically, as well inconsistent with other clients.\r\n\r\nSemantically, 405 means we received a request with a valid path, but an invalid method (like `GET`, `POST`, etc). Per: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Status/405\r\n\r\nWhen sending a 405 we should be sending an `Allow` header back (we do not), but that also doesn't make sense for URLs we don't recognise. I think the correct behaviour would be to return a 404 instead.\r\n\r\n## Version\r\n\r\nLighthouse v2.1.5\r\n\r\n## Present Behaviour\r\n```\r\n$ curl -v \"http://localhost:5052/not_real\"\r\n*   Trying 127.0.0.1:7052...\r\n* Connected to localhost (127.0.0.1) port 7052 (#0)\r\n> GET /not_real HTTP/1.1\r\n> Host: localhost:7052\r\n> User-Agent: curl/7.74.0\r\n> Accept: */*\r\n> \r\n* Mark bundle as not supporting multiuse\r\n< HTTP/1.1 405 Method Not Allowed\r\n< content-type: application/json\r\n< server: Lighthouse/v2.1.5-ffcfef0/x86_64-linux\r\n< content-length: 60\r\n< date: Wed, 23 Mar 2022 03:59:49 GMT\r\n< \r\n* Connection #0 to host localhost left intact\r\n{\"code\":405,\"message\":\"METHOD_NOT_ALLOWED\",\"stacktraces\":[]}\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Steps to resolve\r\n\r\nUntangle the `warp` filters such that we return a 404. There seems to be an issue with 405s taking priority over 404s: https://github.com/seanmonstar/warp/issues/77",
